<article class="prose">
  <h1>About Planet Write-Log</h1>
  <p>
    Planet Write-Log is a community aggregator for sysadmins and IT pros working in the Microsoft
    endpoint management space — ConfigMgr, Intune, Entra, Active Directory, and everything
    in between. It surfaces new blog posts, GitHub releases, and YouTube videos from practitioners
    who share their work — linking directly to their content, never republishing it. The name is a
    nod to the <code>Write-Log</code> function that ends up in just about every PowerShell script
    eventually.
  </p>

  <h2>How to add yourself</h2>
  <ol>
    <li>
      Fork <a href="https://github.com/leghammer-git/planet-writelog">the repository</a>
      on GitHub.
    </li>
    <li>
      Create a new file <code>people/{your-handle}.json</code> following the schema below.
      Your handle must be lowercase alphanumeric + hyphens and match the filename.
    </li>
    <li>
      Open a pull request. CI will validate your JSON against the schema automatically.
      Once merged, you'll appear in the feed within the hour.
    </li>
  </ol>

  <h2>Person file schema</h2>
  <pre><code>{
  "name": "Your Name",
  "handle": "your-handle",
  "title": "Senior Consultant · Endpoint Management",
  "bio": "One or two sentences. 300 characters max.",
  "pronouns": "they/them",          // optional
  "avatar": "https://...",          // optional; falls back to GitHub avatar
  "mvp": {                          // optional
    "status": "active",             // "active" or "former"
    "category": "Enterprise Mobility"
  },
  "links": {                        // all optional
    "website": "https://...",
    "github": "your-handle",
    "bluesky": "you.bsky.social",
    "mastodon": "@you@infosec.exchange",
    "linkedin": "your-linkedin-slug",
    "twitter": "your-handle",
    "youtube": "your-handle"
  },
  "feeds": [
    { "type": "blog",            "url": "https://yourblog.com/feed.xml" },
    { "type": "blog",            "url": "https://shared-blog.com/feed.xml", "author": "Your Name" },
    { "type": "github-releases", "repo": "your-handle/your-repo" },
    { "type": "github-user",     "username": "your-github-username" },
    { "type": "youtube",         "channel": "@YourHandle" }
  ]
}</code></pre>

  <h2>Feed types</h2>
  <dl>
    <dt><code>blog</code></dt>
    <dd>Any RSS 2.0 or Atom feed URL. Add <code>"author": "Your Name"</code> to filter a shared or multi-author feed to only your posts.</dd>
    <dt><code>github-releases</code></dt>
    <dd>Releases from a specific repo you maintain (<code>owner/repo</code>).</dd>
    <dt><code>github-user</code></dt>
    <dd>Pulls the latest release (or most recent push) from each of your public repos. Useful if you maintain many small tools.</dd>
    <dt><code>youtube</code></dt>
    <dd>Your YouTube channel. Use <code>"channel": "@YourHandle"</code> (preferred) or <code>"channel_id": "UCxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx"</code>. Find the ID in YouTube Studio → Settings → Channel → Advanced.</dd>
  </dl>

  <h2>Content longevity</h2>
  <p>
    Blogs move, domains lapse, and sites occasionally disappear overnight. Every feed item includes
    an <strong>Archive</strong> link that points to the <a href="https://web.archive.org/">Wayback Machine</a>.
    Hover over it and the site checks in real time whether a snapshot exists — if one does, the link
    resolves to that specific capture; if not, the link is dimmed to indicate it hasn't been archived
    yet. Not every post will have a snapshot, but for content that matters to you, the
    <a href="https://web.archive.org/save">Save Page Now</a> tool lets you request one manually.
  </p>

